Something I’ve been thinking about recently…

Even from the relaxing pace of winter cabin life, I can feel the dizzying pulse of urgency culture and it makes my head spin.

It’s something I’ve been intentionally witnessing this month - noticing when I’m rushing or feeling the need to do something “asap” or filling downtime with social media and asking myself why.

Sometimes I’ve got a good answer but usually it’s rooted in scarcity.

Like:

-what if the sale ends 
-what if the opportunity goes away if I don’t act now 
-The stillness is a waste of time… I should be doing something productive 
-I’m worried what other people will think if I don’t meet their expectations *as if I truly know what others expect to begin with.
-I’ll let myself down if I don’t finish my to-do list 

Scribble, scribble, scribble away the white space and force the plot along.

Ignoring opportunities for white space in the name of urgency!

If you want to ponder this for yourself, ask:
If my life were a piece of paper, how much white space would there be on todays page?

A few things I’ve been doing this month to create more white space: 

-I moved all social media apps to my iPad. None on my phone
-keeping a “habit tracker” in my journal for the softer things in life like reading, writing, and going for walks.
-completely deleted TikTok 🙄
-only managing emails once per day. If an email comes in after my “office hour” then it’ll get handled the next day.
-maintaining my mental focus on the abundance in life every morning during my walk. 

Would love to hear your tried and true methods for honoring the white space!  Leave me a comment👇

Something I've been wondering about y’all 🤔:

Are any of you big readers??

(I'm not asking if you finish 50 books a year. I'm just asking if you like to read. I'm an embarrassingly slow reader...maybe because I’m always reading 10 books at once 🤷🏻‍♀️)

I gotta know:
1. What kind of books are you typically reading?
2. What was your favorite book last year?
3. What are you reading right now?

Let me know in the comments! 👇
*I could talk books until I’m blue in the face.

I read a handful of non-fiction books and the majority fiction, usually mystery or fantasy...so long as there’s at least a hint of romance in the plot. 

Is it still nerdy to read fantasy? It was when I was a kid.

My favorite book of 2022 was very “on trend” 😆 it was a tie between Verity by Coleen Hoover and the ACOTAR series by Sarah J. Maas.

Currently, I’m reading: Fairy Tale by Stephen King, Twenty Years Later by Charlie Donlea, From Blood and Ash by Jennifer Armentrout, Writing Down the Bones by Natalie Goldberg, and listening to Game of Thrones by George R.R. Martin on Audible with my husband. *told ya, I'm all over the place

✔️We packed our @colemanusa Peak1 20F Mummy Down Sleeping Bags, which kept me warm (but not too warm) at night, during the day in the hammock, and on the shore to watch the sunrise.

Celebrating the fall equinox with an abundant stash of firewood!

Every year, we look forward to this fall task of stocking our wood supply to keep us warm through the winter. We heat our cabin solely with the large barrel wood stove that chews through 6 cords each winter.

*one cord of firewood = 128 cubic feet 

Getting all six cords from the public boat landing where it’s delivered, down the river, and to our cabin takes us about a week!

We can load 1.5 cords onto our barge at a time, meaning it takes 4 round trips up and down the river to get all 6.

It takes us roughly 6 trips with the bucket trailer on the four-wheeler per load. That’s 24 trips with the four-wheeler! 

There’s roughly 600 pieces of firewood in a cord. So 3,600 logs in total that pass through our hands 3 times before even seeing a wood stove.

It sounds like a lot of work and it is but it’s simple, peaceful work that allows us to enjoy time together working towards a shared purpose. 

Inevitably, every year there’s even a few tourists at the public boat launch who lend a hand loading firewood onto our barge!

It’s a tradition we’re quite fond of and wanted to give you a glimpse of! 🫶🏼

P.S. it’s also something we’ll continue to do on a slightly smaller scale when we’ve finished building our house.

The 3 L’s:

1.  What am I LEAVING behind?
2. What am I LOVING right now?
3. What am I LONGING for?

I read about this simple little practice a few months ago and it has stuck for me. My husband and I did this in regard to the new year (macro scale) and I’ve been silently doing this in my head each day on my morning walks (micro scale). It’s the only routine/ritual/practice I’m bringing with me into 2024. Simple and powerful, it helps me cut out the noise and keep a clear eye on the path I want to walk! 🫶🏼

📝Coupla notes:
• With everything I “leave behind”, I try to do so with a sentiment of thanks for whatever it taught me or purpose it served.
• You can think of “loving” in the same way you might write a gratitude list.
• I try to phrase everything I’m “longing for” in the positive, rather than the negative. For example, if you’re excited to ditch a bad habit - instead of saying “I’m longing to stop x,y,z,” try saying “I’m longing/excited/looking forward to having more a,b,c.”

This Canadian Jay is missing the majority of his upper beak. I named him Gepetto six years ago when I moved to the cabin. No matter where I am in camp, he or one of his family seem to follow me, cooing sweetly in a nearby tree branch. 

Also known as Whiskey Jacks, Grey Jays, and Camp Robbers - these birds are quite social. They mate for life, live on the same plot of land their entire life, and can memorize human faces. If they like a person, they can pass that information along to their offspring and same for “bad people”. They’re similar to crows in that way.

It would seem Gepetto marked us as friends because his family still visits our cabin every day. Sadly, I haven’t seen sweet Gepetto in a year and I’ll wager to guess he wasn’t a young pup considering he always had offspring in tow. The average lifespan for a Grey Jay is 8 years.

I’ve so enjoyed befriending him and his family though! The Whiskey Jacks are one of the many animals who make living here feel like a fairytale!
